  "title": "Cable as Community Antenna",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4626f401852c3560",
      "text": "Early cable TV systems in the 1940s and 50s were merely large community antennas picking up distant stations and forwarding them to people's homes. The system slowly evolved, first choosing to select the \"best\" distant stations (even when not local) and later introducing original programming."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fd11e36363cc6321",
      "text": "The original system, then known as CATV (for \"Community Antenna TV\") could serve communities about 100 miles from a traditional broadcast area. The introduction of microwave relay systems in the 1950s changed that, allowing the broadcast of stations to a much larger region. Casper, Wyoming, for example, was provided a Denver station in 1953, despite Denver being nearly 300 miles away."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fea57263c35afa03",
      "text": "As range expanded, providers and consumers started to choose the \"best\" stations instead of the closest. New York and Chicago stations, for example, had larger budgets, better movies, and more sports; by the late 1950s it was common for remote viewers to choose these stations over their \"local\" options."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b325478a7b4c808b",
      "text": "This continued until 1963 when the [[Carter Mountain Decision]] came through."
    }
